We cooked for family, real and imagined, informally, formally, somewhere between the two.
We cooked for friends who were happy or troubled, for people in programs that had them floating a line between the two.
We know that children who eat with their families regularly do better in school.
They saw the time spent in pews as silly and boring, a waste of time they might have better spent reading manga or doing homework.
The words of Michael Pollan should ring true for Sunday dinners as in the rest of our diet: &;Eat food.